Hardly any change can be conceived greater than that which takes place at what is called the ‘instant‘ os death. Now, this so-called instant is in reality tivo: the last oi Life, the sust os Non-Life. Until and at that last moment ol lise, it is true that the man, though dying, is living; at that moment it is yet salse to say that he is dead. But, ‘He is dead’, becomes true immediately afterwards. The former instant is not the latter, though there is no possible interval between them. And as it is evident that in every change - though not so apparently - there is the same succession ol distinct, yet immediate, instants, and as we know that the duration ol everything real is a reality, it follows that those indivisible elements ol duration are also real.

How then, in this theory, are we to conceive movement as taking place? As the infinitesimal instantaneous passage uf one punctal atom from the site which it occupies to the next, its former site never remaining empty, but being at once and of necessity filled hy the next punctal atom. What is called a slow continuous motion is continuous to the senses only, it consists of a multitude of instantaneous hut infinitely short leaps‚ with intervals os more or fewer instants os rest between them.
